      "kwargs": {
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "{\"success\":true,\"process_rule_id\":\"J09B\",\"process_rule\":\"1. From the source decision table, create a working table `J09B_temp` containing only rows where the tour identifier starts with `J09B`.\\n\\n2. In table `J09B_temp`, add a new column `ENTSCHEIDUNG` (string) to hold the meter reading type.\\n\\n3. Classify meter reading type by filling `ENTSCHEIDUNG` in `J09B_temp` using these rules, in this order:\\n   - For each `HAUS`, count how many `EQUNR` it has.\\n   - If a `HAUS` has fewer than 3 `EQUNR`, set `ENTSCHEIDUNG = \\\"KSA\\\"` for all rows of that `HAUS`; else set `ENTSCHEIDUNG = \\\"EVU\\\"`.\\n   - Then override to `\\\"EVU\\\"` for any row where:\\n     - `HOUSE_NUM1 = 0`, or\\n     - `HOUSE_NUM1` is in the range `500–599`, or\\n     - `HOUSE_NUM1` is in the range `900–999`.\\n\\n4. Join `J09B_temp` with the `EABLG` table using `INSTALLATION` as the join key (preserve all rows from `J09B_temp` and enrich them with matching `EABLG` data).\\n\\n5. Join the result with both `NET_MASTER` and `SALES_MASTER` tables using `EQUNR` as the join key (i.e., join with `NET_MASTER` and `SALES_MASTER` on `EQUNR` and bring their customer data into the working table).\\n\\n6. Compare the customer data coming from `SALES_MASTER` and `NET_MASTER` for each row to determine whether the sales customer data is available (i.e., whether the relevant `SALES_MASTER` customer fields are not empty for that row).\\n\\n7. Decide which customer master data to use for each row:\\n   - If the sales customer data for the row is NOT empty (condition “sales customer data NOT empty”):\\n     - Use the customer data fields from the `SALES_MASTER` table for that row as the definitive customer data in the working table.\\n   - Else:\\n     - Use the corresponding customer data fields from the `NET_MASTER` table for that row as the definitive customer data in the working table.\\n\\n8. Export the final content of the working table as a CSV file named `J09B.csv`.  \\n   - Ensure the CSV has exactly these column names (spelled as below):  \\n     `Meter Reading (MR) Doc. No.`, `HAUS`, `ANLAGE`, `ME_MA_ID`, `EQUNR`, `HOUSE_NUM1`, `ENTSCHEIDUNG`, `TITLE`, `FORENAME`, `SURNAME`, `STREET`, `STREETNO`, `POST_CODE1`, `CITY1`, `CITY2`, `EMAIL`.\\n\\n9. Send an email to the EVU with the CSV file:\\n   - Recipient email address: `meter.readings@evu.com`.\\n   - Attach the exported file from the path indicated as `file_path: <path_to_exported_csv_file>` (use the actual path where `J09B.csv` was saved).\\n   - The email must include the attached `J09B.csv` file.\\n\\n10. After the email has been sent successfully, delete the temporary working table `J09B_temp` from the system.\\n\\n11. End the process.\"}",
            "id": "lc_593f7756-b070-46fb-9d2b-b6ed2beda05b"
          }
        ],
        "type": "tool",
        "name": "retrieve_process",
        "id": "846bd183-3a21-4ccc-bcf0-8660a46a004d",
        "tool_call_id": "call_BwaEC6ZYhjc6tvK5OTnMEyC6",
        "artifact": {
          "structured_content": {
            "success": true,
            "process_rule_id": "J09B",
            "process_rule": "1. From the source decision table, create a working table `J09B_temp` containing only rows where the tour identifier starts with `J09B`.\n\n2. In table `J09B_temp`, add a new column `ENTSCHEIDUNG` (string) to hold the meter reading type.\n\n3. Classify meter reading type by filling `ENTSCHEIDUNG` in `J09B_temp` using these rules, in this order:\n   - For each `HAUS`, count how many `EQUNR` it has.\n   - If a `HAUS` has fewer than 3 `EQUNR`, set `ENTSCHEIDUNG = \"KSA\"` for all rows of that `HAUS`; else set `ENTSCHEIDUNG = \"EVU\"`.\n   - Then override to `\"EVU\"` for any row where:\n     - `HOUSE_NUM1 = 0`, or\n     - `HOUSE_NUM1` is in the range `500–599`, or\n     - `HOUSE_NUM1` is in the range `900–999`.\n\n4. Join `J09B_temp` with the `EABLG` table using `INSTALLATION` as the join key (preserve all rows from `J09B_temp` and enrich them with matching `EABLG` data).\n\n5. Join the result with both `NET_MASTER` and `SALES_MASTER` tables using `EQUNR` as the join key (i.e., join with `NET_MASTER` and `SALES_MASTER` on `EQUNR` and bring their customer data into the working table).\n\n6. Compare the customer data coming from `SALES_MASTER` and `NET_MASTER` for each row to determine whether the sales customer data is available (i.e., whether the relevant `SALES_MASTER` customer fields are not empty for that row).\n\n7. Decide which customer master data to use for each row:\n   - If the sales customer data for the row is NOT empty (condition “sales customer data NOT empty”):\n     - Use the customer data fields from the `SALES_MASTER` table for that row as the definitive customer data in the working table.\n   - Else:\n     - Use the corresponding customer data fields from the `NET_MASTER` table for that row as the definitive customer data in the working table.\n\n8. Export the final content of the working table as a CSV file named `J09B.csv`.  \n   - Ensure the CSV has exactly these column names (spelled as below):  \n     `Meter Reading (MR) Doc. No.`, `HAUS`, `ANLAGE`, `ME_MA_ID`, `EQUNR`, `HOUSE_NUM1`, `ENTSCHEIDUNG`, `TITLE`, `FORENAME`, `SURNAME`, `STREET`, `STREETNO`, `POST_CODE1`, `CITY1`, `CITY2`, `EMAIL`.\n\n9. Send an email to the EVU with the CSV file:\n   - Recipient email address: `meter.readings@evu.com`.\n   - Attach the exported file from the path indicated as `file_path: <path_to_exported_csv_file>` (use the actual path where `J09B.csv` was saved).\n   - The email must include the attached `J09B.csv` file.\n\n10. After the email has been sent successfully, delete the temporary working table `J09B_temp` from the system.\n\n11. End the process."
          }
        },
        "status": "success"
      }
    },
